svg.desc: The chart shows the Gini coefficient of household income in OECD countries in 2014. The Gini coefficient is calculated on a scale of 0 to 1. The higher the figure, the greater the inequality. Of the 35 OECD countries depicted, Germany ranked 13th with a coefficient of 0.29. Scoring 0.25, Iceland, Slowakia and Slovenia had the lowest Gini coefficient of household income and Costa Rica scoring 0.49, had the highest.
